Text scrolls across the screen: 

Awaiting Input...

Effects of the Virus on Kinrath Biology:

One of the few experiments on non-sentient lifeforms. The subject in question was injected with the virus as per usual, and immediately began to degrade. Communication isn't the same as with those who can actually speak in some way, but based on its actions it appeared to suffer the same detrimental effects on its mind, losing all self control in the process. But as per all other subjects, effects remain entirely consistent through expiration, decomposition, and reanimation.

Tests will continue. End of log.

Effects of the Virus on Twi'lek Biology:

Perhaps due to their basic similarities to humans as a whole, save for a few things of course, the subject appears to suffer the effects much the same as a human. Like all subjects, the twi'lek subject in question succumbs to acute loss of self-awareness and bodily control over only a few minutes after initial exposure. Some discolouration at the ends of the lekku could be noted, but it was also inconsistent with other twi'lek subjects to be proven as an effect of the virus itself.

Putting that aside, events proceeded as normal. Expiration then reanimation after a short time of rapid decomposition.

Tests will continue. End of log.

Effects of the Virus on Whiphid Biology:

While it was rather difficult to perform a direct injection on such a creature, we did eventually manage. Within minutes, it began to show similar symptoms of insanity, consistent with every other test subjects. But the physical abnormalities separate it from the others.

While necrosis isn't unusual in these tests, shortly after initial injection, the site began to suffer from heavy swelling and rapid necrosis. Following this, it seemed to rapidly develop sores all over its body that quickly popped open and began spewing out think discharges of blood and puss. It was also noted that the tusks on the whiphid's lower jaw quickly changed colour to that of a sickly yellow shade.

Even prior to death, the insanity almost seemed to give it a boost in strength, which ultimate led to the deaths of two personnel in the containment unit. Aside from that, however, the death and reanimation seems consistent with other subjects.

Tests will continue. End log.

Effects of the Virus on Neti Biology:

Acquiring a specimen of this sort likely was no easy task for the recovery team. That said, it aids in our research on the effects across multiple species. Anyways, to move on to the effects themselves, the loss of self-awareness and control appears entirely consistent with the rest, however it appears to progress at a drastically slower rate. While other subjects entered that stage and expired within only minutes of exposure, the neti subject took well over an hour.

Through that time during proper incubation, physical abnormalities could also be noticed. While initially the subject appeared much as a healthy tree, as neti tend to, the bark on them slowly began to turn dark brown and black, and eventually started molting. The branches that serves as their limbs appear to atrophy and start clumping together in closer knit bundles.

Where other subjects appeared to suffer effects of decomposition post-expiry, it's much like this subject began experiencing it pre-expiry. Accompanying the overall rotting tree appearance it began to take on, it also started giving off a powerful molding, decaying stench, that you may often smell in an old swamp.

Following actual expiration, however, effects continue to remain consistent with each other subject. Reanimation as normal.

Testing will continue. End of log.

Effects of the Virus on Rodian Biology:

For the most part, initial exposure to the virus remains much the same as human and twi'lek biology. However, shortly before before expiration, the subject in question began violently and consistently vomitting. So much so that it ultimately vomitted up its own organs, which led to death less than a minute later. It's interesting to note, as well, as despite losing the organs, the reanimation process still proceeds as usual and the subject was capable of moving about and even making those unnatural screams that they're known to do. It appears they don't require vital organs of those sort, at least, to continuing "living".

Tests will continue. End of log.

Effects of the Virus on Human Biology:

Following initial exposure to the injection, within minutes the subject began showing acute loss of self-awareness and control over their body. Shortly after, the subject expired, pronounced dead by research personnel on site. After death, the body showed signs of rapid decomposition, but then halted in the early to advanced stages. As has been consistent with past subjects, the reanimation process took over shortly after.

One interesting thing to note amongst all subjects is the unnatural screaming they seem to do on occasion. Each time it's done, it's answered in kind by subjects in other cells. It's almost like they're communicating in some way we can't understand.

Testing will continue. End of log.

Effects of the Virus on Wookiee Biology:

After initial exposure to the virus, the effects remain consistent with that of any other species. Apparent loss of sanity over only a few minutes. However, there are a few differences that should be noted. The test subject in question began screaming about wookiee younglings and how mounds of its clan and children were burning, rotting, and melting even. Shortly after, the more physical irregularities could be noticed.

The wookiee's throat began to inflate, much like a balloon, as it started choking and gagging, suffocating from whatever fluid was likely building up. It eventually grew so much that it even popped like such a balloon, leading the wookiee to expire within only a few seconds from blood loss. If it hadn't happened, though, it's likely it wouldn't have been long before the suffocation would have done so.

Prior to the reanimation process that was evident in all other subjects, closer inspection revealed an acute swelling of the tongue, as well, blocking off any and all air through the throat. Bit harsh if you ask me. Suffocation, either way.

Following reanimation, it shows aggression consistent with the other subjects, though perhaps a bit more-so due to the difference in strength with a wookiee.

Tests will continue. End of log.
